<LEADPARA>  ASK James Mason why the anthology "When I Am an Old Woman I Shall Wear Purple"
has sold 200,000 copies, an astounding number for a book from a small
publisher, and he'll tell you it's certainly not because Watsonville-based
Papier-Mache Press has a large advertising budget.;    "Firstly, it taps a
very much neglected and increasingly vast senior citizen market," says Mason,
marketing manager for Papier-Mache Press, which three years ago published the
anthology of stories, poems and photographs about growing old. "And the
combination of simple, evocative language and photographs has given the book
an astonishing word-of-mouth promotion."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WHEN LITTLE BOOKS HIT IT BIG  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Books  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Professional word-of-mouth promotion, when booksellers recommend their
favorites to customers, is known in the industry as "hand selling," and over
time it often can turn a little-known book such as "When I Am an Old Woman I
Shall Wear Purple" into something of a best seller.;    It's that kind of
word-of-mouth promotion the American Booksellers Association wants to
encourage with its first-ever ABBY award, announced early this month. The
$5,000 award, voted on by ABA-member bookstores, will be presented at the
association's June meeting in New York.;    "When I Am An Old Woman I Shall
Wear Purple" was named one of three runners-up in the competition. Another
steady seller that seemed unlikely to make the leap to best seller, "The
Education of Little Tree," got top honors as the American Booksellers Book of
the Year.;    "The Education of Little Tree" is Forrest Carter's
autobiographical account of his 1930s boyhood spent with his Cherokee
grandparents in the Appalachian Mountains of Tennessee.;    Carter, who died
in 1979 at the age of 53, also wrote the novel "Gone to Texas," which was made
into the Clint Eastwood film "The Outlaw Josey Wales." Still, his name was
hardly a household word on a par with Sidney Sheldon or Louis L'Amour when
"The Education of Little Tree" was published by Delacorte in 1976.;    The
book was warmly if not widely reviewed. The Atlantic noted that, "Some of it
is sad, some of it is hilarious, some of it is unbelievable and all of it is
charming.";    A paperback edition was published by Dell/Laurel Leaf in 1981.
Word spread and, over the years, "The Education of Little Tree" became a cult
classic, even though the book went out of print.;    Five years ago, though,
the University of New Mexico Press brought out a $10.95 trade paperback
edition that has sold almost a quarter of a million copies. It has been the
press's best-selling book for two straight years and sales show no sign of
abating; more than 25,000 copies were shipped out in January and February.;   
Similarly, Papier-Mache Press plans to publish a hardcover edition of "When I
Am an Old Woman I Shall Wear Purple" in July. The hardcover book, which will
sell for $16, will be issued simultaneously with an updated paperback version
priced at $10.;    Other runners-up for the ABBY award were the best-selling
"The Civil War," by Geoffrey Ward with Ric Burns and Ken Burns, the companion
volume to the popular PBS series; "The Shell Seekers," a novel by Rosamunde
Pilcher that also made best-seller lists; and "Cold Sassy Tree," the late
Olive Ann Burns' novel about family relationships in a small Georgia town.;   
The awards process began in January, when booksellers nominated the five books
they most enjoyed hand selling in 1990. Any book in print, fiction or
non-fiction, was eligible. In February, the ABA announced the 10 ABBY
finalists as culled from the 2,000 nominations made by more than 400
booksellers. Final voting took place in March.;    In the weekly ABA
newsletter, executive director Bernie Rath noted that one of the intentions of
the ABBY award program was to generate a list for bookstores of titles that
sell steadily over time, the so-called midlist books.;    The other five
finalists for the ABBY were Barbara Kingsolver's novels "Animal Dreams" and
"The Bean Trees"; Fannie Flagg's funny novel "Fried Green Tomatoes at the
Whistle Stop Cafe"; Kazuo Ishiguro's critically acclaimed novel "The Remains
of the Day"; and Jill K. Conway's memoir of her Australian girlhood, "Road
from Coorain."  </TEXT>
