<HL> Get Ready, World:
Now Donald Trump
Wants a Best Seller
---
Real-Estate Tycoon Begins
Media Blitz to Sell Book;
The Party in the Atrium
---
By Laura Landro and Laurie P. Cohen
Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 11/30/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> PUBLISHING (PUB) </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real-estate tycoon Donald Trump loves to think big. 
And in the case of his new book, maybe a bit too big. 
Just listen: 

   "The book has gone out in an unusual number of copies," he says. 
"Two hundred thousand." 
Well, not exactly. 
In fact, 150,000 have been printed. 

   "Today" will feature him in "five segments," he says. 
Well, not quite. 
The NBC show plans only two. 

   A recent New York magazine cover story that excerpted his book was "the biggest seller they ever had," he says. 
Maybe or maybe not. 
The magazine doesn't get its sales figures back for at least 60 days. 

   If Mr. Trump has been caught playing a bit loose with the facts, he probably won't mind. 
"A little hyperbole never hurts," he says in his book. 
"I call it truthful hyperbole. 
It's an innocent form of exaggeration -- and a very effective form of promotion." 

   All hype aside, Mr. Trump and Random House Inc., his publisher, have big plans for "Trump: The Art of the Deal." 
The book, in which Mr. Trump shares the secrets of his success for $19.95 a copy, has already hit New York bookstores, and it is now making its debut nationwide. 

   "If a person has an instinct for making deals, they'll make a fortune by reading this book," promises Mr. Trump. 

   Prepare yourself for more Trumpisms. 
In the next few weeks, the book will get one of the most extraordinary publicity blitzes ever for a new book. 
Wake up to Mr. Trump on "Today," watch him later in the day ("Donahue") or at night (with Barbara Walters on "20/20"), or nod off to the sound of his voice on "Late Night With David Letterman." 
If you miss those appearances, your local television station may be one of 12 scheduled for live satellite interviews. 

   You can also catch up with Mr. Trump at the supermarket in People magazine or read the Philadelphia Inquirer, the Chicago Tribune or the Washington Post. 
If all else fails, visit one of Mr. Trump's Atlantic City casinos or Trump Tower in Manhattan. 
Chances are he will be there in person autographing books. 

   "Donald's ambition is to outsell Lee Iacocca. 
That's what this is all about," says "60 Minutes" correspondent Mike Wallace, who wrote a glowing blurb for the book ("This reads like Trump unvarnished -- vainglorious, combative, ambitious and unafraid to let us know about it!"). 

   Mr. Wallace doesn't think Mr. Trump's book will actually outsell "Iacocca," and Random House isn't saying that it's that ambitious. 
The Chrysler Corp. chairman sold 2.6 million copies in hard cover alone. 
But Random House has a lot at stake here: its reputation for picking winners and the $1 million advance it gave Mr. Trump. (The developer says he is giving all proceeds to charity.) 

   Mr. Trump initially agreed to write an autobiography two years ago at the request of Random House owner S.I. Newhouse Jr. 
Several months later, writer Tony Schwartz, interviewing Mr. Trump for a Playboy magazine article, suggested that the developer might be too young at 39 to be writing his memoirs. 
Besides, Mr. Schwartz said, people might be more interested in Mr. Trump's deal-making prowess. 
Mr. Trump agreed, signed on Mr. Schwartz as co-writer, and the rest is history. 

   Following Mr. Schwartz's suggestion, the book is short on personal details. 
It notes that Mr. Trump was born into a wealthy real-estate family in the borough of Queens, left college with a mere $200,000, and married Ivana, a former skiing star and fashion model. 
But the focus of "Trump" is deal-making, specifically Mr. Trump's unfailing ability to swing real-estate deals despite the opposition of such foes as New York Mayor Edward Koch. 

   Mr. Trump's renown in New York seems sure to sell the book here; the president of Doubleday Book Shops, Gary DelVecchio, says that the book has sold "phenomenally" at its store across from Trump Tower. 

   "Today, business tycoons are cult heroes with the masses -- they live vicariously with the yachts and the helicopters," says Leonard Riggio, the president of Barnes &amp; Noble Inc., which also owns the national B. Dalton Booksellers chain. 
"Trump has a world-class ego and a world-class appetite -- let's hope he has a world-class audience." 

   Mr. Trump is certain his growing national reputation will help sell books. 
In the past year he has appeared on the covers of Fortune, Business Week and Newsweek; the recent Newsweek cover was the magazine's seventh-best seller this year. ("It should be; he bought 10,000 copies himself," says a Newsweek spokeswoman.) 
As a result of such exposure, Mr. Trump says, "this book looks like it will be just as big in Los Angeles and the Midwest as it is in New York." 

   But some booksellers aren't so sure. 
"I don't think it will be a big book in Chicago," says Harlan Smith, a buyer for the 17-store Kroch's &amp; Brentano's chain in Chicago. 
Mr. Smith thinks that Mr. Trump's highfalutin style may not go over well in the Midwest. 
"We like things a little more basic -- not as glitzy," he says. 

   Rhett Jackson, the proprietor of the Happy Bookseller in Columbia, S.C., and the president of the American Booksellers Association, couldn't quite recall the Trump book at first. 
"What's the name of it?" he asks. 
His chief book buyer informs him that the store bought 10 copies instead of the 20 pressed on it by its Random House salesperson. 
"Business books have taken a pretty sharp dive in the last 18 months," says Mr. Jackson. 
"And we're not sure how well known he is in these parts." 

   "We don't think it's going to sell anything like it will in New York," says David Sisk, a buyer for the Bookstop chain in Austin, Texas. 
Mr. Sisk bought about 395 copies for his 13 Texas stores, compared with an initial order of 1,200 copies of T. Boone Pickens's book last year. 
And while B. Dalton's New York-based owners are enthusiastic about the book, a saleswoman at the chain's store in Pittsburgh's Century III Mall led a customer to a back shelf and said, "People aren't that interested in Donald Trump around here. 
We don't think this will sell too well in this part of the country." 

   But Susan Russenberger, who buys books for Ingram Book Co., a wholesaler that serves chain and independent stores, is more optimistic. 
"When Random House prints 150,000 copies of a book, that's something you can almost bank on," she says. 
She agreed to buy 15,000 copies for her customers in June after Random House told her that "Donald Trump is very interested in selling this book and is going to exert a lot of energy into making a success." 

   She got that right. 
In between deal-making, giving speeches on nuclear disarmament, fighting with Mayor Koch and hinting that he may run for president, Mr. Trump has tirelessly campaigned to promote his book. 
In May, he spent part of his Memorial Day weekend at the American Booksellers convention in Washington. 

   Along with Mr. Newhouse, Mr. Trump exhorted a group of book retailers and wholesalers to get out there and sell, sell, sell his book. 
Mr. Newhouse, who rarely attends such meetings and almost never speaks publicly, told the crowd that he had made two great decisions in publishing: buying Random House and signing Mr. Trump to write a book. 

   Mr. Trump didn't stop at that. 
He hopped up to Stamford, Conn., to have a meeting with regional managers of the Waldenbooks chain, the country's largest. 
He took some powerful book executives to lunch, including Mr. Riggio of Barnes &amp; Noble. 
Over lunch at La Cote Basque in New York, "he told me he'd really like to see the book do well," says Mr. Riggio. 
"He has a great instinct for promotion -- he gets in touch, tugs you by the collar and pats you on the back." 

   To promote the book in its New York flagship store, Barnes &amp; Noble has created a "Trump Tower" display. 
It may even sell copies from pushcarts on Fifth Avenue. 
Waldenbooks has created a "power aisle" -- a display of signs and books -- in its stores. 
Its customer newsletter includes reservation coupons for the book, and the chain's business-gift catalog features "Trump" prominently in an ad for a toll-free gift-ordering service. 

   There will also be a book party, of course. 
Mr. Trump has invited 3,000 of his closest friends for music and dancing in the atrium of Trump Tower. 
Two of his pals, Steven Rubell and Ian Schrager, the founders of the disco Studio 54, are taking care of the details. 
"It will be the party of the year," Mr. Trump promises. 

   But New York's cognoscenti may have trouble staying awake. 
Trump Tower has Mr. Trump's name on it; the atrium, however, is considered a public place, and private parties that start before 10 p.m. require city approval. 
As it happens, New York won't let Mr. Trump start his party early, and some believe that the decision came from Mayor Koch himself. 
New York newspapers recently quoted Mr. Trump describing the mayor as "a moron" during a public dispute over the developer's proposed Television City project. 
A spokesman for Hizzoner will say only that "the mayor says he's not talking about Donald Trump anymore." 

</TEXT>
