<AUTHOR> Cynthia Crossen (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> WCI </CO>
<IN> PUB </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Books will pay more than $500,000 for the paperback rights to the best-selling "Trump: The Art of the Deal." 

   Final terms are still being discussed. 

   Warner, a subsidiary of Warner Communications Inc., outbid three other publishing companies for the book, written by Donald Trump, a New York real estate developer. 
With 700,000 hardcover copies in print, the book has topped the New York Times best-seller list for the past three weeks. 

   Random House editors had privately expressed concern that the book's popularity in hardcover might have saturated its market, and damped enthusiasm for the paperback rights. 
However, industry observers said the price for the paperback rights indicates Warner Books has high expectations for it. 

   Paperback rights for nonfiction bestsellers have ranged recently from $400,000 to about $1.2 million. 
Authors typically get at least half the proceeds from the sale of such rights. 
Mr. Trump has said he will donate all book proceeds -- including his share of the paperback rights -- to charity. 

   Warner said its first printing will be a least one million copies and perhaps as high as two million. 

   Warner had taken a so-called floor position of $350,000 on the book; Warner had thus guaranteed Random House Inc., publisher of the hardcover, at least that much for the paperback rights. 
In return, Warner had the right to top by 10% the highest bid from any other publishing concern. 
Bantam Books was the second highest bidder. 

   Laurence Kirshbaum, president of Warner Books, said the company recognized the sales potential of "Trump" at a Random House sales conference in Palm Beach, Fla., in early December. 
"Everyone from Random House was talking about just one book -- 'Trump,'" he said. 
"So we cornered the subsidiary rights director at the swimming pool and said we want the floor. 
We didn't sit there and play with our numbers. 
We jumped on it." 

   Mr. Kirshbaum added: "I think our competitors undervalued the 'Trump' book. 
But that's their problem." 

</TEXT>
