<LEADPARA>  IN AN effort to learn more about the origins of the Middle East crisis,
readers are cleaning bookstore shelves of works about Iraq and Saddam Hussein,
local booksellers report.;    "We have a list of about 40 key titles (on the
Middle East), and we've sold out of a few," said Michael Davis, district
manager for the San Francisco Bay Area for B. Dalton Books. Davis added that
some publishers have sold out of their stock of Middle East books and have had
to rush to reprint.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE STUDY OF WAR
READERS SEARCH FOR INFORMATION ON CRISIS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  War in the Gulf
Books  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Readers are grabbing copies of two books in particular, "Saddam Hussein and
the Crisis in the Gulf," by Judith Miller and Laurie Mylroie, and "Republic of
Fear: The Inside Story of Saddam's Iraq," by Samir al-Khalil, booksellers
said.;    "Those are the ones that are scooped up very readily," said Clark
Kepler, owner of Kepler's Books &amp; Magazines in Menlo Park. "I think it's due
to the curiosity that we all have for a man and a party and a culture that
mystifies us.";    But not only books about Iraq and Saddam are selling
briskly, Davis said.;    "There is great interest and significant sales . . .
of books on auxiliary topics, like the Arab/Israeli conflict, Islam and
terrorism," he said. "Books on the peace movement and non-violence are selling
very well.";    So are books on the Vietnam war and World War II, said Miriam
Springer, a clerk at "A Clean, Well-Lighted Place for Books" in Cupertino,
where the shelves are emptying of books about the Middle East rapidly.;    And
maps of the Middle East are also disappearing, said Stuart Henderson, manager
of Printer's Inc. bookstore in Palo Alto.;    Along with the two books about
Saddam, Henderson said "A Peace to End All Peace: The Fall of the Ottoman
Empire and the Creation of the Modern Middle East," by David Fromkin (Avon,
1989. 567 pages, $14.95, paperback), and "From Beirut to Jerusalem," by Thomas
L. Friedman, are the big sellers.; Here's a Gulf reading list of current
titles:; (box) "Republic of Fear: The Inside Story of Saddam's Iraq" by Samir
al-Khalil. (Pantheon/Random House, 1989. 312 pages, $12.95, paperback.); (box)
"Saddam Hussein and the Crisis in the Gulf" by Judith Miller and Laurie
Mylroie. (A Times Special Report, 1990. 268 pages, $6.95, paperback.); (box)
"From Beirut to Jerusalem" by Thomas L. Friedman. (Anchor/Doubleday, 1989. 541
pages, $12.95, paperback.) 21 weeks on the New York Times paperback
best-seller list.; (box) "The Rape of Kuwait: A True Story of Iraqi Atrocities
Against a Civilian Population" by Jean P. Sasson. (Knightsbridge Publishing,
1990. 154 pages, $4.95, paperback.); (box) "The Future Battlefield and the
Arab-Israeli Conflict" by Hirsh Goodman and W. Seth Carus. (Transaction
Publishers/Near East Policy Series, 1990. 218 pages, $10.95, paperback.);
(box) "The Saudis: Inside the Desert Kingdom" by Sandra Mackey.
(Meridian/Penguin, 1987. 433 pages, $9.95, paperback.); (box) "Arabs: Journeys
Beyond the Mirage" by David Lamb. (Random House, 1987. 320 pages, $9.95,
paperback.); (box) "Arab and Jew: Wounded Spirits in a Promised Land" by David
K. Shipler. (Penguin, 1986. 596 pages, $12.95, paperback.); (box) "The
Crusades Through Arab Eyes" by Amin Maalouf. (Schocken, 1985. 312 pages,
$12.95, paperback.); (box) "The Kingdom: Arabia and the House of Sa'ud" by
Robert Lacey. (Avon, 1981. 630 pages, $5.95, paperback.); (box) "The Big Book
for Peace" by 30 authors and illustrators of children's books. (Dutton
Children's Books, 1990. 120 pages, $15.95, hardcover.); (Source for reading
list: The Los Angeles Times)  </TEXT>
